## 1. Candidate-Based ROI Inference (CPU Optimization via TFLite)

One of the largest bottlenecks on the Raspberry Pi 4B is running heavy neural networks on full hardware-resolution frames. Processing a 640x360 image continuously can crater FPS down to single digits.

**Solution:**
We use deterministic, light-weight computer vision (CV) to extract localized candidate regions ("hotspots") and pass only these small patches to an ARM-optimized TensorFlow Lite (`tf.lite.Interpreter`) model.

1. **Thermal Masking:** We threshold the Thermal grayscale frame (pixel > 180) to instantly isolate potential fire boundaries using the CPU-friendly `cv2.threshold`.
2. **Top-K Sorting:** We compute the localized `minMaxLoc` of extracted contours and select the Top-10 highest-temperature coordinates.
3. **Patch Cropping & Prediction:** For the Top-10 coordinates, isolated bounding patches are projected and mapped onto the RGB fusion space. 
   - We dynamically interrogate the TFLite Model graph via `interpreter.get_input_details()` to ascertain its required input resolution (e.g., 224x224 or 320x320) and dtype (Float32 / UInt8).
   - We apply OpenCV resizing/normalization on the CPU to pass standard `[1, H, W, 3]` tensors efficiently.
4. **Execution Interval:** This heavy TF operation is constrained to execute exactly once per second (`frame % fps == 0`). During intermediary frames, the system relies on previously tracked spatial intersections, assuring stable real-time FPS delivery > 15-20.

